    {"Z":95,"sym":"Am","name":"Americium","group":3,"period":7,"cat":"act","ar":243,"appearance":"silvery white","phase":"Solid","density":12,"melt":1175.85,"boil":2606.85,"molar_heat":62.7,"discovered_by":"Glenn T. Seaborg","electron_configuration":"[Rn] 5f7 7s2","electron_affinity":9.93,"electronegativity":1.13,"ionization_energy":578,"shells":[2,8,18,32,25,8,2],"summary":"Americium is a radioactive transuranic chemical element with symbol Am and atomic number 95. This member of the actinide series is located in the periodic table under the lanthanide element europium, and thus by analogy was named after the Americas. Americium was first produced in 1944 by the group of Glenn T.Seaborg from Berkeley, California, at the metallurgical laboratory of University of Chicago.","source":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Americium","spectral_img":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Americium_spectrum_visible.png","bohr_model_image":"https://storage.googleapis.com/search-ar-edu/periodic-table/element_095_americium/element_095_americium_srp_th.png","bohr_model_3d":"https://storage.googleapis.com/search-ar-edu/periodic-table/element_095_americium/element_095_americium.glb"},
    {"Z":96,"sym":"Cm","name":"Curium","group":3,"period":7,"cat":"act","ar":247,"appearance":"silvery metallic, glows purple in the dark","phase":"Solid","density":13.51,"melt":1339.85,"boil":3109.85,"discovered_by":"Glenn T. Seaborg","electron_configuration":"[Rn] 5f7 6d1 7s2","electron_affinity":27.17,"electronegativity":1.28,"ionization_energy":581,"shells":[2,8,18,32,25,9,2],"summary":"Curium is a transuranic radioactive chemical element with symbol Cm and atomic number 96. This element of the actinide series was named after Marie and Pierre Curie – both were known for their research on radioactivity. Curium was first intentionally produced and identified in July 1944 by the group of Glenn T. Seaborg at the University of California, Berkeley.","source":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curium","bohr_model_image":"https://storage.googleapis.com/search-ar-edu/periodic-table/element_096_curium/element_096_curium_srp_th.png","bohr_model_3d":"https://storage.googleapis.com/search-ar-edu/periodic-table/element_096_curium/element_096_curium.glb"},
    {"Z":97,"sym":"Bk","name":"Berkelium","group":3,"period":7,"cat":"act","ar":247,"appearance":"silvery","phase":"Solid","density":14.78,"melt":985.85,"boil":2626.85,"discovered_by":"Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory","electron_configuration":"[Rn] 5f9 7s2","electron_affinity":-165.24,"electronegativity":1.3,"ionization_energy":601,"shells":[2,8,18,32,27,8,2],"summary":"Berkelium is a transuranic radioactive chemical element with symbol Bk and atomic number 97. It is a member of the actinide and transuranium element series. It is named after the city of Berkeley, California, the location of the University of California Radiation Laboratory where it was discovered in December 1949.","source":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berkelium","bohr_model_image":"https://storage.googleapis.com/search-ar-edu/periodic-table/element_097_berkelium/element_097_berkelium_srp_th.png","bohr_model_3d":"https://storage.googleapis.com/search-ar-edu/periodic-table/element_097_berkelium/element_097_berkelium.glb"},
